': 'PLAUSIBLE', 'conviction_multiplier': 1.0}, {'contract_month': '202605', 'prediction_type': 'DIRECTIONAL', 'direction': 'BEARISH', 'reason': "The debate is genuinely contested at the fundamental level, but the weight of independent evidence tilts bearish when properly contextualized. Let me count the independent lines of evidence on each side.\n\nBULLISH SIGNALS: (1) Supply Chain Report — EPNG force majeure trapping Permian gas, LNG feedgas at 18 Bcf/d, storage at meaningful deficit. (2) Inventory Report — 132 Bcf withdrawal, regional East/Midwest deficits of 16-17% below 5-year average, falling rig count. (3) Sentiment Report — non-commercial net shorts at -198.5K contracts creating short-squeeze potential. (4) Macro Report — power burn at 72% thermal share with 13.4% YoY consumption increase. However, critically, the Macro and Geopolitical Reports both independently identify the 'false causation fallacy' in the LNG bullish thesis: physical export terminal caps prevent the global supply shock from creating uncapped Henry Hub demand pull. This degrades the quality of the LNG narrative from a strong independent signal to a capped, partially priced-in catalyst.\n\nBEARISH SIGNALS: (1) Technical Report — price failed at $3.3027 resistance, broke below $3.139 daily pivot, two consecutive significant down days, price 13.4% below 200-day SMA. (2) Volatility Report — CVOL at 98.529 (neutral directionally but extremely expensive options, triggering mandatory thesis_strength downgrade per framework rules). (3) Macro Report — domestic production at 107-110 Bcf/d robust, weather 7.2% warmer than 30-year normal, export capacity caps the upside. (4) Geopolitical Report — geopolitical risk premiums fading per de-escalation signals and G-7 reserve release threats. (5) Inventory Report self-critique — the 115 Bcf YoY surplus is a meaningful bearish offset the bulls underweight, and the storage deficit framing relies on unverified consensus figures.\n\nCRITICAL SYNTHESIS POINTS: 